Based on other spp from this family in CCS there was both bathypelagic and benthopelagic (which I changed to bathypelagic based on Eschemeyer). I looked up other spp in this genus on ITIS and there were bathypelagic, bathydemersal, pelagic-oceanic and bentho-pelagic life histories represented. Based on literature reference: Poulsen 2015 Zootaxa "They are all small-mouthed elongated fishes separated primarily on continous characteres and ususally found in the mesopelagic realm between 200 and 1000m". While it is possible that other depths occur, because of this general genus description and the evidence that both representative spp in the database are mesopelagic, I am going to identifiy as mesoepalgic here.

Eschemeyer: "Oceanic, usually near surface; possibly near bottom." Miller & Lea "Depth, surface to 120 ft, but usually in greater depths well offshore. " Janssen and Harbison 1981 state:"Young Tetragonurus live in the upper waters, whereas adults are mesopelagic or bathypelagic and migrate to the surface waters at night (FItch, 1951, Grey 1955, Tononaka 1957, Ahlstrom 1969).  They eat mainly salps and pyrosomes. (and can be found in the body cavities of salps). " Based on all of these accounts, I am going to define these as mesopelagic because in their adult stage at daytime they appear to inhabit mesopelagic depths.
